Danish Health Authority Responds to Eric Feigl-Ding's Viral Tweet About the Country‚Äôs COVID-19 Death Data

üá©üá∞@COVID19Up: The Danish infectious disease agency State Serum Institute has tweeted several times in English in recent days in response to criticism of the country‚Äôs decision to lift COVID-19 restrictions, including by Eric Feigl-Ding, an American with over 600,000 followers on Twitter.

The State Serum Institute (SSI), the equivalent of the U.S. CDC, responded to Feigl-Ding, who in one viral tweet, accused the Danish government of ‚Äúlosing its frigging mind‚Äù and ‚Äúgaslighting‚Äù the country‚Äôs population over its decision at the beginning of February to largely end COVID-19 restrictions.

‚ÄúDear Eric, once again we would like to stress that the numbers you are sharing with your followers shows (sic.) deaths with (Covid)-19. Not deaths because of (Covid)-19. We would recommend that you read our weekly report for more information on the subject,‚Äù SSI tweeted in response.

Feigl-Ding also claimed that COVID-19 deaths in Denmark were ‚Äúexponentially surging‚Äù as a result of restrictions being lifted.

But an SSI chart was posted in response showing a distinction between deaths caused by COVID-19 and deaths ‚Äúwith‚Äù Covid-19 and not caused by it, based on death certificate information. The chart shows the number of deaths caused by COVID-19 to be stable.

Technology and Social Media
Microsoft founder Bill Gates (1993), former Microsoft CEO Steven Ballmer (2000-2014, selected in 1995), Amazon founder Jeff Bezos (1998), Google co-founders Sergey Brin and Larry Page (2002/2005), former Google CEO Eric Schmidt (2001-2011, selected in 1997), Wikipedia co-founder Jimmy Wales (2007), PayPal co-founder Peter Thiel (2007), eBay co-founder Pierre Omidyar (1999), Facebook founder and CEO Mark Zuckerberg (2009), Facebook COO Sheryl Sandberg (2007).
